\begin_layout Exercise
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a prime number, 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},\ldots,a_{n}\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Prove that if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\mid a_{1}a_{2}\cdots a_{n}
\]

\end_inset

then 
\begin_inset Formula $p\mid a_{i}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We want to show that the open sentence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P\left(n\right):\,\text{if \ensuremath{p\mid a_{1}a_{2}\cdots a_{n}} then p\mid a_{i} for some 1\leq i\leq n }
\]

\end_inset

is true with 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 a prime number, 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},\ldots,a_{n}\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 We work this by induction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\series bold
Base Case
\series default
: We verify 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

 we have that if 
\begin_inset Formula $p\mid a_{1}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $p\mid a_{i}$
\end_inset

for some 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 Since we only have one 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $p\mid a_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 The statement 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

 was proven in Thm 19.5 of the book.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\series bold
Induction Step
\series default
: We suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, and that 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

 is true.
 We want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(k+1\right)$
\end_inset

 is true which is the statement: if 
\begin_inset Formula $p\mid a_{1}\cdots a_{k+1}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $p\mid a_{i}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq k+1$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $b=a_{1}\cdots a_{k}$
\end_inset

 such that we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $p\mid ba_{k+1}$
\end_inset

.
 We know from Thm 19.5 that if 
\begin_inset Formula $p\mid ba_{k+1}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $p\mid b$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $p\mid a_{k+1}$
\end_inset

.
 This gives us two cases.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Case
If 
\begin_inset Formula $p\mid a_{k+1}$
\end_inset

, then were done.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Case
If 
\begin_inset Formula $p\mid b$
\end_inset

, then since we suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

 to be true, we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $p\mid a_{i}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq k$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(k+1\right)$
\end_inset

 is true.
 Therefore the open sentence 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(n\right)$
\end_inset

 is true.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
