\begin_layout Exercise
The goal of this exercise is to prove that there are infinitely many primes
 which are congruent to 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 modulo 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

.
 We will do this in a series of steps.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Prove that, with only one exception, every prime number is congruent to
 either 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 modulo 3.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Proof
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 be a prime number greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

.
 This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $3\nmid q$
\end_inset

.
 Since every 3rd natural number is a multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

, we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $3\mid\left(q+1\right)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $3\mid\left(q+2\right)$
\end_inset

 since either 
\begin_inset Formula $q+1$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $q+2$
\end_inset

 will be a multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $q+2$
\end_inset

 is a multiple of three, then 
\begin_inset Formula $q+2-3=q-1$
\end_inset

 is a multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $3\mid q+1$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $3\mid q-1$
\end_inset

.
 This is equivalent to saying that every prime number greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 is congruent to either 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 modulo 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

.
 The last two prime numbers that we need to investigate are 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

.
 Well 
\begin_inset Formula $2+1=3$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $3\mid2+1$
\end_inset

 thus 
\begin_inset Formula $2\equiv-1\,\text{mod}\,3$
\end_inset

.
 Lastly 
\begin_inset Formula $3\mid3$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $3\nmid\left(3\pm1\right)$
\end_inset

 and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 is not congruent to either 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 modulo 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we have shown that every prime number other than 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 is congruent to either 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 modulo 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Prove that for any 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 and any 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},\ldots,a_{n}\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, if each 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}\equiv1\,\text{mod}\:3$
\end_inset

, then the product 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}a_{2}\cdots a_{n}\equiv1\,\text{mod}\,3$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Proof
We want to show that the open sentence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P\left(n\right):\,\text{if each a_{i}\equiv1\,\text{mod}\:3 , then the product a_{1}a_{2}\cdots a_{n}\equiv1\,\text{mod}\,3 }
\]

\end_inset

is true for any 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 and any 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},\ldots,a_{n}\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 We work this by induction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\series bold
Base Case
\series default
: We verify 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}\equiv1\:\text{mod}\,3$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2}\equiv1\:\text{\mod}\,3$
\end_inset

 which is equivalent to saying 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}-1=3m_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2}-1=3m_{2}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1},m_{2}\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Using these identities, the product 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}a_{2}$
\end_inset

 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
a_{1}a_{2} & =\left(3m_{1}+1\right)\left(3m_{2}+1\right)\\
 & =3\cdot3m_{1}m_{2}+3m_{1}+3m_{2}+1\\
 & =3\left(3m_{1}m_{2}+m_{1}+m_{2}\right)+1
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{1}a_{2}-1=3k,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $k=3m_{1}m_{2}+m_{1}+m_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This is equivalent to saying 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}a_{2}\equiv1\,\text{mod}\,3$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

 is true.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\series bold
Induction Step
\series default
: We suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(j\right)$
\end_inset

 is true for some 
\begin_inset Formula $j\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, and we want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(j+1\right)$
\end_inset

 is true.
 We begin with writing the product 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{1}a_{2}\cdots a_{j}a_{j+1}=ba_{j+1}.
\]

\end_inset

Since we assume 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(j\right)$
\end_inset

 to be true, we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $b\equiv1\,\text{mod}\,3$
\end_inset

.
 This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $b=3y_{b}+1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{j+1}=3y_{j+1}+1$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{b},y_{j+1}\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Taking their product we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
ba_{j+1} & =\left(3y_{b}+1\right)\left(3y_{j+1}+1\right)\\
 & =3\left(3y_{b}y_{j+1}+y_{b}+y_{j+1}\right)+1
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ba_{j+1}=3\ell+1
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell=3y_{b}y_{j+1}+y_{b}+y_{j+1}$
\end_inset

.
 This is equivalent to saying 
\begin_inset Formula $ba_{j+1}=a_{1}a_{2}\cdots a_{j}a_{j+1}\equiv1\,\text{mod}\,3$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(j+1\right)$
\end_inset

 is true.
 Therefore the open sentence 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(n\right)$
\end_inset

 is true for any 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
