\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:prime_odd"

\end_inset

Every prime number other than 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 is odd.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We suppose directly that 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is a prime number and let 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 be a prime number greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

.
 Since the only positive divisors of a prime number is itself and 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $q\neq2m$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, otherwise the prime number 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 would have 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 as a divisor, at which point it wouldn't be a prime number.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $2\nmid q$
\end_inset

 thus 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is odd.
 Since the prime number 
\begin_inset Formula $2=2k$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, it is even.
 Thus we have shown that every prime number other than 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 is odd.
 
\end_layout

